HPI:
Mr. Smith is a 70 year old African American male with PMH of HTN, COPD, HLD, and BPH who presents to MS ER with shortness of breath that started yesterday. He states he had a dry cough 2-3 days ago. He has associated wheezing and intermittent pleuritic chest pain. He says he uses his Proair and Advair at home which which provided some relief. He says he's supposed to receive a CPAP next month and currently uses 3L of O2 at home. He had COVID in 2020 and is fully vaccinated for COVID19.
He also complains of a perineal lesion that he noticed about 1 week ago. He said it was a "small bump" but has gotten bigger and worse. It became more sore with drainage and odor that he noticed yesterday. He uses a wheelchair and walker at home and says he was unable to sit comfortably. He has associated constipation.
He denies any fevers, chills, nausea, vomiting, or diarrhea. [1]
Hospital course:
Mr. Smith is a 70-year-old African-American gentleman with past medical history of COPD, chronic respiratory failure on 3 L oxygen at home, hypertension, hyperlipidemia, BPH, GERD who presented to the ER with the complaints of shortness of breath and rectal pain. On presentation, chest x-ray did not show any acute cardiopulmonary abnormalities. CT abdomen and pelvis with contrast showed left gluteal subcutaneous inflammatory process and a small perineal abscess. Patient was started on IV antibiotics and a general surgery was consulted. General surgery did bedside I&D. Blood and wound cultures were sent. Blood cultures were negative. Wound culture showed mixed flora. Patient was also noted to be in no acute exacerbation of COPD and he was started on prednisone. Patient's symptoms slowly improved and he returned to baseline now. He was discharged home in stable condition on prednisone taper, Augmentin and doxycycline.
Patient was seen and examined on the day of discharge. Plan of care was discussed with the patient. Time spent was 32 minutes.
